# BrightScript Pitfalls & Crash Prevention

## Invalid / Uninitialized Access (Most Common Crash)

The #1 cause of BrightScript crashes is accessing a member on `invalid`. Always guard:

```brightscript
' CRASH — if getItem() returns invalid, .title dereferences invalid
title = getItem().title

' SAFE
item = getItem()
if item <> invalid
    title = item.title
end if
```

- `findNode()` returns `invalid` if the ID doesn't exist — always check the result.
- Chained dot access (`a.b.c.d`) is dangerous; any link being `invalid` crashes the app.
- Content fields from `ContentNode` may be unset — use `hasField()` or provide defaults.

## Type Mismatch Crashes

BrightScript has no implicit type coercion between incompatible types:

```brightscript
' CRASH — cannot add string and integer
result = "Count: " + 5

' SAFE
result = "Count: " + Str(5)
result = "Count: " + 5.ToStr()
```

- Arithmetic on `invalid` crashes. Validate before math: `if value <> invalid and type(value) = "Integer"`.
- Comparing mismatched types (e.g., `String` vs `Integer`) crashes — normalize types first.
- `Val()` returns 0 on non-numeric strings but crashes on `invalid` — check before calling.
- Passing wrong argument types to a function crashes at call site with no helpful stack trace.

## Array / Index Out of Bounds

```brightscript
' CRASH — index beyond array length
items = ["a", "b", "c"]
value = items[5]

' SAFE — bounds check
if index >= 0 and index < items.Count()
    value = items[index]
end if
```

- `roArray` does not auto-expand on read. Writing beyond bounds silently extends, but reading does not.
- `for i = 0 to items.Count()` is off-by-one — use `items.Count() - 1`.
- Mutating an array (`.Delete()`, `.Push()`) while iterating with `for each` causes undefined behavior.

## Node / Component Lifecycle

- Accessing a node after `removeChild()` or setting its parent to `invalid` crashes if you still hold a reference.
- `getParent()` returns `invalid` inside `init()` — do not navigate the tree upward during initialization.
- `createObject("roSGNode", "TypeName")` returns `invalid` if the component XML has errors — always check.
- Calling `setFocus(true)` on a node not in the scene tree is a silent no-op, leaving the UI unresponsive.

## Observer & Callback Pitfalls

- Using `observeField` instead of `observeFieldScoped` leaks observers. Leaked observers accumulate and fire on destroyed components, causing crashes.
- Observer callbacks receive an `roSGNodeEvent` — calling `getData()` on it can return `invalid` if the field was cleared before the callback fires.
- Setting a field inside its own observer creates an infinite loop that freezes the render thread.
- Observing fields on nodes from a different thread context (e.g., render thread observing a task field with a callback) triggers excessive Rendezvous.

## Task Thread Crashes

- Any unhandled error in a Task thread silently kills that task — the `state` field changes to `"stop"` with no visible error unless you're watching the debug console.
- `sleep()` in a task with `0` or negative value causes undefined behavior — always use positive values.
- Calling SceneGraph node functions (e.g., `appendChild`, `removeChild`) from a Task thread crashes. Only read/write fields — never call node methods.
- Forgetting to set `functionName` before setting `control = "run"` crashes the task immediately.

## String Handling

- `Mid()`, `Left()`, `Right()` with out-of-range indices crash rather than returning a truncated result. Clamp indices to `Len(str)`.
- `Instr()` returns 0 (not -1) when the substring is not found. Index 0 also means "found at position 0" — this ambiguity causes logic bugs.
- String concatenation in tight loops creates massive GC pressure. Build an array and `join()` for bulk string assembly.

## Network & I/O

- `roUrlTransfer.GetToString()` blocks the calling thread. Never call it on the render thread — use an async pattern with a Task.
- Forgetting to call `SetCertificatesFile("common:/certs/ca-bundle.crt")` before HTTPS requests causes silent failures (empty response, no crash).
- Not setting `EnableEncodings(true)` means gzip responses arrive as raw compressed bytes, parsed as garbage.
- File operations (`ReadAsciiFile`, `WriteAsciiFile`) return empty string or `false` on failure, not exceptions — always check return values.
- `cachefs:/` has limited space (~256KB–1MB depending on device). Writing large files silently fails.

## Memory & Performance Traps

- Roku devices have limited RAM (512MB–2GB). Large image arrays or unbounded caches cause `EXIT_OUT_OF_MEMORY`.
- Bitmaps not visible on screen still consume texture memory. Set `uri = ""` or remove poster nodes when off-screen.
- Creating many nodes dynamically without removing old ones leaks memory. Use object pools or `MarkupGrid`/`RowList` for large lists.
- `Eval()` recompiles on every call. Never use it in loops or frequently called functions.
- `roRegex.Match()` compiles the pattern each time if you create a new `roRegex` per call. Cache the `roRegex` object.

## Focus & Key Handling

- If no node has focus, the remote becomes unresponsive. Always ensure *something* has focus after any screen transition or dialog dismissal.
- `onKeyEvent` must return `true` when handling a key, otherwise the event bubbles up and may trigger unintended behavior in parent components.
- Returning `true` for the "back" key without providing an alternative exit path traps the user — Roku certification will reject this.
- Rapid key presses can queue multiple `onKeyEvent` calls. Guard state transitions to avoid double-navigation.

## Conditional Compilation & Platform

- `#if` / `#else` / `#end if` constants come from `bs_const` in the manifest. Referencing an undefined constant is a compile-time error that prevents the app from launching.
- Firmware version checks via `roDeviceInfo.GetVersion()` return a string, not a number. String comparison works for major versions but breaks for minor version comparisons (e.g., `"9.4" > "9.30"` is `true` because of lexicographic ordering). Parse version segments as integers.

## Defensive Coding Checklist

Before shipping, verify:

1. Every `findNode()` result is checked against `invalid`
2. Every network response is validated before field access
3. No `STOP` statements remain in code
4. No blocking calls exist on the render thread
5. All observers use `observeFieldScoped`, not `observeField`
6. Array indices are bounds-checked
7. All `for each` loops handle empty collections
8. Focus is explicitly set after every screen transition
9. Task `functionName` is set before `control = "run"`
10. String-to-number conversions guard against `invalid` input
